\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The institution has submitted additional information. According to the evaluator most of the concerns raised in the initial evaluation have not been addressed.  The curriculum content still does not include the Typing\'2FComputer component which is inherent in this type of qualification.  This should be a progression from the Higher Certificate Office Administration.    It was suggested that Public Relations can then be introduced at this level because the learners have already grasped the fundamentals in Marketing I.  This has not been done.  Instead the institution has included Economics I\'2C which could be an elective in the Diploma.  Again\'2C the Industrial Relations content could be incorporated into the Human Resources module to cater for the Computer-related module.  The content of the Office Administration module need to be upgraded to include more advanced themes like conference and events management\'2C arranging travel and accommodation\'2C the art of networking\'2C etc.  These recommendations were disregarded and more managerial-related concepts like problem solving and quality management were included.  One area of concern is the fact that the department is using the same prescribed book  for two separate subjects\'2C Advanced Office Administration and Advanced Business Administration.  The Work Integrated Learning \'28WIL\'29 content is the same as that of the Higher Certificate. \line \line A list of professional bodies and associations the institution has affiliated and collaborating with is only in the Accounting\'2C Commerce and Information Technology sphere.  Office Administration related bodies are still lacking and these are of paramount importance when the institution is offering this type of programme. Such bodies include an Association for Office Professionals of South Africa \'28OPSA\'29 and the IAAP.\line \line In terms of selection and recruitment the evaluator is of the opinion that requiring learners to have competence in End User Computing limits access.  Instead the institution should have mechanisms in place to address any deficiencies in this skill.  The Age exemption and RPL practices not clearly spelled out.\line \line The issue of flooding the market is of concern in some of the cities.  For example\'2C there are more than two learning sites in Pretoria\'2C Braamfontein and Johannesburg.  The evaluator recommended that the programme be offered in one learning site in these cities during its initial phases and be extended to others as time progresses.\line \line The evaluator also thought that Criterion 3 is in need of improvement in the sense that staff are qualified in the Business and Commercial field which is not relevant to Office Administration. \line \line In terms of facilities the evaluator was of the opinion that a practicum room is a necessity for this programme.\line \line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the programme should not be accredited.  \cell \pard 

